    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix integer overflow in UE_RNTI function array access\n\n### Summary\nThe UE_RNTI function in the eNB scheduler was vulnerable to integer overflow when accessing the UE_template array. The function used the UE_PCCID return value directly as an array index without bounds checking, which could lead to out-of-bounds memory access.\n\nThis fix adds proper bounds checking before array access to prevent potential buffer overflows and undefined behavior.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/LAYER2/MAC/eNB_scheduler_primitives.c`: Added bounds checking for array indices in UE_RNTI function\n\n### Reproduction\nWhen the eNB receives a message with an invalid UE ID or when UE_PCCID returns an invalid carrier component ID, the function could access memory outside the allocated UE_template array boundaries. This could result in:\n- Segmentation fault due to invalid memory access\n- Return of garbage RNTI values\n- Potential security vulnerabilities from reading uninitialized memory\n\nThe issue is triggered when:\n1. ue_idP is negative or >= MAX_MOBILES_PER_ENB\n2. UE_PCCID returns a value that is negative or >= NFAPI_CC_MAX\n\nWith the fix, the function now properly validates both indices and returns NOT_A_RNTI (0) for invalid inputs, preventing the overflow condition.\n"
}